-culture of rural Scotland with a consummate linguistic artistry to become not only the world's most popular love poet but also the controversial master poet of modern democracy. Written with accessible elan and nuanced attention to Burns's poems and letters, The Bard is the story of an extraordinary man fighting to maintain a sly sense of integrity in the face of overwhelming pressures. This incisive biography startlingly demonstrates why the life and work of Scotland's greatest poet still compel the attention of the world a quarter of a millennium after his birth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh  aAberdeenshire.  aAdams, John.  aAiken, Andrew Hunter.  aAlexander, Wilhelmina.  aAlloway.  aAmerican Revolution.  aArmour, Jean.  aAyr.  aAyrshire.  aBannockburn.  aBarskimming.  aBelles Lettres.  aBirmingham.  aBonhams auctioneers.  aCabinet of Genius.  aCalvinism.  aCarleton, General.  aCatholicism.  aClackmannanshire.  aCreech, William.  aDalquhatswood.  aDalrymple.  aDumfresshire Volunteers.  aEdinburgh Magazine.  aEdinburgh.  aExcise service.  aFarming.  aFergusson, Robert.  aFrance and the French.  aFreemasons.  aFrench Revolution.  aGalloway.  aGlasgow Magazine.  aHamilton, Gavin.  aHanoverians.  aIpecacuanha.  aIrvine.  aJacobites.  aJamaica.  aKeith, Earl Marischal.  aKilmarnock.  aLawrie, Archibald.  aLondon Magazine.  aMcLehose, Agnes.  aNewmilns.  aNithsdale.  aOchterhouse.  aPeacock, Mary.  aPope, Alexander.  aRainie, Agnes.  aRamsay, John of Ochtertyre.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400832842zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400832842423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400832842.jpg  aEBA_BACKAL